{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_grindylow_ver01/data/sn85040652/00414215579/1913122001/0326.xml":{"full_text":"DIGESTOF WORLD\u2019S\nIMPORTANT NEWS\nEPITOME OF THE BIG HAPPEN\nINGS OF THE WEEK.\nTO BE READ AT A GLANCE\nItems, Both Foreign and Domestic,\nThat Have Interest for Busy Read\ners, Arranged and Classified\nfor Their Convenience.\nWashington\nAndrew Carnegie takes little stock\nin rumors of business depression,\neither present or Impending. At the\nWhite House in Washington when\nasked what he thought of the general\nbusiness outlook, Mr. Carnegie said:\n\u201cThe recent reports of impending\nwidespread business depression are\nall tommy rot.\"\n\nThe Administration currency bili\nwas subjected to many attacks dur\ning the debate in the senate at Wash\nington.\n\nA sweeping investigation of transit\nrates on live stock over railroads in\nwestern classification territory was\nordered by the interstate commerce\ncommission at Washington.\n\nMountain Laurel is proposed as the\nofficial national flower of the United\nStates in a bill introduced in the\nhouse at Washington by Representa\ntive Klnkead of New York.\n\nPresident Wilson has taken more\ncold and canceled all his engagements\nby order of bis physician. Chief Jus\ntice White and Justice Burton also are\nconfined to their homes in Washington\nsuffering with colds.\n\nThe house at Washington waR turned\ninto a fcircus for an hour and a half\nRepresentatives Hobson and Hartholdt\ndebated the prohibition question be\nfore crowded galleries. Underwood\nrose repeatedly to charge Mr. Hobson\nwith misrepresenting liirn.\n\nGovernment ownership of telegraph\nand telephone lines is being serious\nly considered by the president. Con\nferences between the president and\nPostmaster General Ilurleson at Wash\nington have led to a gathering of in\nformation about the practical work\nings of government ownership in other\ncountries.\n\nSecretary of War Garrison in his\nannual report said the time had not\nyet come for disarming or slackening\nthe nation's efforts for preparedness\nin case of war. He also declared the\npresent provision for an army reserve\nis not working satisfactorily.\n\nA petition for national prohibition\nby constitutional amendment was\npresented to President Wilson and\ncongress by a committee of 1,000.\n\nCounsel for Margaret Catherine Sul\nlivan, seventeen years old, obtained\nfrom the supreme court an order to\ncompromise for $50,000 her claim\nagainst the estate of Representative\nTimothy D. Sullivan, Tammany leader.\nIt had not been known until this ac\ntion was taken that \u201cBig Tim\" had a\ndaughter.\n\nThe report of the house lobby inves\ntigating committee at Washington se\nverely censures Representative Mc-\nDonald and asserts that the National\nAssociation of Manufacturers and oth\ner organizations have maintained an\nimproper lobby in Washington. It\ndoes not recommend or suggest any\naction by congress upon these find\nings\nt\nWhere President Wilson will spend\nhis Christmas vacation, it he takes\none, will be left to the \"Main House.\u201d\nThis is the president's way of saying\nMrs Wilson and the Misses Wilson\nwill make the selection.\nDomestic\nWith Us starboard main-shaft pro\npuller broken and several of its com\npartments flooded, the battleship Ver\nmont is on its way toward Hampton\nroads on the return trip from the\nMediterranean cruise. It is under\nconvoy of the battleship Delaware and\nthe colliers Orton and Jason.\n\nThe Harvard seniors at Cambridge.\nMass., have elected a negro, Alexan\nder L. Jackson of Englewood, N. J\u201e j\ntheir orator for class day, t','l4.\n\nJoseph Anderson was shot and\nkilled by Mamie Lindsey at Lan\ncaster. Pa It is said that the dead\nman was Jealous of his son who\nhad eclipsed him In winning the af\nfections of the woman. She was ar- j\nrested\n\nA bomb delivered in the office of\nthe O K. Bottling company. 528-530\nWest Thirty-eighth street. New York.,\nexploded and killed an eighteen-year\nold girl, Ida Anusewitz Thomas Mc-\nCabe, the office manager, was fatally\nhurt.\n\nHeath electric chair for Hans\nSchmidt, trie renegade priest, who\nconfessed the murder of Anna Aumul\nler, was demanded by Assistant Dis- j\ntrict Attorney J. ,4. Delahanty in his\nopening address to the Jury in New\nYork.\nThe motorcycle corps of the New\nYork police department of 23 men has\narrested more than 13,000 i>ersonB In\nj the last year. The total of fines im\nI posed has been over $117,000.\n\nPere Marquette railroad was fined\nI $6,100 and the Wabash assessed $4OO\nby Judge Arthur J. Tuttel in the United\nStates court at Detroit, Mich., the for\nj mer for failure to obey in full the fed\neral railroad laws, and the latter for\nthe violation of the safety appliance\nlaw.\n\nSheriff Smith of Bingham. Utah, re\nfused to grant the request of Mrs. W.\nS. Coo and Mrs. Alvida M. O. Carls,\nwho asked that they be permitted to\nenter the TJtah-Apex mine and try to\ninduce Ralph Lopez, Mexican desper\nado and slayer of six men, to surren\nder.\n\nAthur Schwlchow is on his way\nfrom Nashville, Tenn., to Wheaton,\n111., to face a charge of murder for\nthe killing of Edmund Rotermund.\nassistant cashier of the Addison State\nbank, October 25. Cecil Baker, whose\nfriendship for Sehwichow brought\nabout his arrest, has been held as an\naccessory.\n\nCharges that the American Tele\nphone and Telegraph company, the\nCentral Union Telephone company and\nthe Chicago Telephone company con\nspired to wreck the Interstate com\npany and drive it from the competing\nfield in Illinois, were made in a bill\nfiled in the circuit court on behalf of\n78 bondholders of the Interstate com\npany.\nAfter an all-night search Sheriff\nRussell captured three suspects for\nsafe blowing at Lawler, la. The men\nhad $l6O In money, many gold rings\nand a complete outfit of burglar tools.\n\nThe Safety and Sanitation confer\nence opened In New York and the\nspeakers said that while great strides\nhave been made In the last decade in\nthe direction of safety for shop work\ners, there Is much yet. to be done.\n\nMexican Revolt\nRead Admiral Fletcher, commande>\nof the American naval forces in Mex\nican waters, ordered the rebels and\nfederals fighting at Tampico to cease\nfiring, threatening to open upon them\nwith the guns of the gunboat Wheel\ning if his order was not obey. Both\nsides obeyed.\n\nAmericana who arrived at El Raso,\nTex., from Chihuahua reported that\nsince their occupation of that city the\nrebels had entered the British vice\nconsulate and forcibly seized Luis Ter\nrazas, Jr., a son of the wealthiest land\nowner in Mexico and placed him in\nJail.\n\nThe Mexican congress nullified the\nrecent presidential election. New\nelections were called. In voting that\nthe presidential election of October\n26 was null the deputies decided to\nfix the first Sunday In July, 1914, as\nthe date for the new election. They\nalso confirmed the position of Huerta\nas provisional president until then.\nForeign\nThe Ilussian government proposed\nthe withdrawal of all foreign troops\nfrom Pekiug and the entire province\nof Chi-Ll, China, Including the lega\ntion guards, the regiments at Tientsin\nand the troops guarding the railway\noetween the sea and Peking. Russia\nconsiders conditions in the north of\nChina no longer dangerous to foreign\ners.\n\nA newspaper advertising campaign\nfor recruits to the British army Is to\nbe undertaken In all parts of Great\nBritain. The war office has become\nconvinced of the value of the news\npapers? as a medium\n\n\"Mona Lisa,\u201d ILeonardo da Vinci's\nmasterpiece, the mysterious disap\npearance of which from the Louvre\nIn August, 1911, threw the art world\ninto consternation, was found in Flor\nence, Italy. The man who stole it was\narrested.\n\nGreat excitement was caused on the\nbourse at Madrid. Spain, by the fail\nure of the Banko His p&no-Americano,\na $20,000,000 institution, to open its\ndoors.\n\nJohn Holloway, vice-chairman of\nthe port docks board, was shot during\na riot between nonunion coal men and\nstriker's at Dublin.\n\nla'oti la>tort. a well known French\naviator, was killed at Harbezieux, De\npartment of Charente, France. July\n14 Letort made a record nonstop\nflight of 590 miles from Haris to Her\nlin in eight hours.\n\nMiss Helen Goudy of Chicago, noted\nbeauty of the American colony, be\ncame the bride of Lieut Gerard\nof the First Life guards. The wed\nding took place In St. Geprge's Han\nover square, London.\n\nThe city council of Paris, France, re\njected the proposal to restore sisters\nof charity and the members of other*\nnursing orders to the posts they held j\nin the Ihtris hospitals prior to the sep j\naration of churrh and state.\n\nPersonal\nWilliam Astor Chattier. African S\nplorer and author, is suffering in\nParis, Prance, from Injuries unstained\niu an automobile Vcident ten days\nago. An operation |>n one of his legs\nwill be necessary. I\nIRON COUNTY NEWS, HURLEY, WIS.\nCONVENTION OF\nMACHINE DEALERS\nEighth Annual Meeting Is Opened\nin Milwaukee.\nMORE THAN 300 ARE PRESENT\nExhibit of Implement Men in Audi\ntorium Reviewed by Delegates\u2014\nR. H. Brewer Delivers Presi\ndent's Address.\nMadison. \u2014The eighth annual con\nvention of the Wisconsin Retail Imple\nment and Vehicle Dealers' association\nopened in Milwaukee.\nHeadquarters are at the Auditorium,\nwhere the manufacturers are holding\nan exhibit.\nMore than 300 delegates were pres\nent at the opening session.\nR. H. Brewer of Ripon delivered the\npresident\u2019s address. The state asso\nciation will elect new officers before\nthe close of the convention.\nThe present officers are: President,\nR. 11. Brewer, Ripon; vice-president,\nJames B, Watson, Fond du Lac; secre\ntary and treasurer, F. R. Sebenthall,\nEau Claire. Directors: William Vic\ntoria, Muscoda: Herman Fessenfeld,\nBlack Earth; Earl Robbins, Eau\nClaire; 1,. H. Waite, Seymour, and\nGustav Hochardt, South Milwaukee.\nCrowds thronged the Auditorium\narena the opening day of the conven\ntion. More delegates inspected the\nvaried exhibits than attended the busi\nness sessions held.\nThe exhibit hall contains a hundred\nbooths in which are everything of need\nto the farmer from a package of seed\nto a gas engine.\n$192,515 in Motor Licenses.\nWith the fiscal year at. an end, the\nissuing of licenses for auto vehicles\nand dealers in the office of Secretary\nof Slate Donald has practically closed.\nThe record shows licenses issued for\nthe year, together with the revenue\nderived as follows:\nAutomobiles, 34,646 at $5 $173,230\nMotorcycles, 6,120 at $2 12,240\nDealers, 1,377 at $5 6,885\nDealers, 16 at $lO 160\nTotal $192,515\nOn August 1, the law increasing the\nfee for dealers from $5 to $lO went in\nto effect, which accounts for the two\nrates for that class.\nAuto licenses issued in 1912 num\nbered 24.478, an increase of 10,06s for\n1913.\nThe revenue from licenses is used\nin the building and repairing of high\nways.\nSecretary of State Donald is prepar\ning for the rush season of 1914. Al\nready over 100 applications have been\nreceived. The new number plates are\nto bo in yellow hack ground with em\nbossed white figures.\nWisconsin Man Elected.\nThe alfalfa growers of the country,\nmindful of the advantage of co-opera\ntion. recently organized the National\nAlfalfa Growers\u2019 association. The aim\nof this organization is to create a more\ngeneral interest, in the growing and\nuse of alfalfa, to encourage the study\nof alfalfa as a forage crop, to deter\nmine more economical ways of hand\nling and feeding alfalfa and otherwise\nto encourage alfalfa growing.\nDr. J. E. Oheeseman of Racine was\nelected one of the vice-presidents of\nthe new association, and R. A. Moore\nand L. F. Graber of the College of Ag\nriculture, H. E. Krueger of Beaver\nDam, E. H. Webster of Fort Atkinson\nand Peter Schwartz of Waukesha were\nchosen as directors.\nAccording to Mr. Graber, who is the\nsecretary of the Alfalfa Order of the\nWisconsin Agricultural Experiment as\nsociation. there Is not a county in Wis\nconsin in which alfalfa is not grown,\nand this forage crop is* constantly be\ncoming more and more popular with\nWisconsin farmers.\nTrust Firms Close Meeting.\nThe annual meeting of the Asso\nciated Trust Companies of Wisconsin,\nat the offices of the First Savings and\nTrust company in Milwaukee, resulted\nin the election of the following of\nficers\nPresident E B. Steensland. Madi\nson.\nVice-President \u2014G 1\u2019 Stickuey Mil\nwaukee.\nSecretary ami Treasurer U L\nSmith. Milwaukee.\nTwenty one delegates ore present,\nthose from outside of Milwaukee be\ning G, A Knapp. K J. Ferry and H.\nR. Potter, Fond du Lac; E. Steens\nland and L. M. Hanks, Madison: John\nBoland. Green Bay; W H. Purnell,\nKenosha, and Judge Emil Baensch.\nManitowoc,\nG. P Stickney was elected vice\npresident of the trust section of the\nAmerican Bankers' association.\n772.304 Children in School.\nThe school census of tiie state, an\nnounced by State Superintendent O. P\nCary, shows there are 772,304 children\nof school age in Wisconsin. This is\n3,169 less than the number reported\nlast year. The reduction is accounted\nfor by the greater accuracy of the re\nports. duplications being almost entire\n-I.' avoided.\nMilwaukee county leads the list with\n138. 6vy as compared with 151..913 last\nyqar. Dane county is next with 22,Adi.\ncompared with 23,862 in 912.\nState Grange Select* Antlgo.\nNearly the entire catagory o' ooliti\njcal and economic reforms an seated\nin state and nation we-v indorsed by\nj adopted by ihe 100 dele\ngates of the State Grange of Wiseon\nsin. Patrons of husbandry In session\nat Rhinelander.\nResolutions were adopted favoring\nthe principle of the referendum and\ni recall, improvement of the income tax\nlaw, woman suffrage, supervision of\nguarantee of bank deposits, extension\nj of the system of county agricultural\nj representatives, government owner-\nI ship, improvement in parcel post and\nj direct vote of people for presidential\nnominees.\nThe convention also favored a more\nliberal policy of the state in assisting\nnew settlers in clearing land and pro\ntested against what they called the\nGriffith policy of appropriating agri\ncultural lands for forestry purposes.\nAntigo was chosen as the next con\nvention city in 1914.\nMaster. H. M. Culbertson, Medina:\noverseer, William Menning. Apple\nton: lecturer. Emma Wilde, Rhinelan\nder; steward, P. Gillette, Antigo;\nchaplain, A. C. Powers, Beioit; treas\nurer, Arthur Krause, Allenville: secre\ntary, George H. Dawes, Tomahawk\ngate keeper, E. K. Riek, Rhine\nlander; Ceres, Mrs. Eva Howe, An\ntigo; Pomona. Mrs. Martha Bogenreif,\nWashburn; Flora, Mrs. Susie Mcln\ntosh, Rhinelander; member executive\ncommittee, H. Howe, Antigo.\nState Poultry Show in January.\nInterest in poultry raising will be\ngiven an added impetus in this state\nJanuary 5-9, when the Wisconsin\nPoultry association will hold its tenth\nannual exhibition at the live stock pa\nvilion in Madison.\nIt is thought that 1,500 birds will\nbe shown by the various exhibitors\nfrom all parts of Wisconsin.\nThe officers of the Wisconsin Poul\ntry association are: President, Frank\nSweeney, Arglye; first vice-president,\nM. C. Gerard, Stoughton; second vice\npresident, J. F. Johns, Dodgevilie; sec\nretary, Janies G. Halpin, Madison;\ntreasurer, William H. Milward, Madi\nson. The official judges are George\nHackett, North Freedom, and W. S.\nRusseli, Ottumwa, la. The board of\ndirectors consists of Rear Admiral\nF. M. Symonds, Galesvllle; Dr. A. L.\nFosse, Cambridge; William Bell, Ar\nlington; William Thomas, Belleville;\nand J. 11. Borden, Madison.\nCollects for Exhibit Fund.\nWork on the collection of $16,000 to\ndefray the expenses of a Wisconsin ex\nhibit at Ihe centennial at Christiania.\n.Norway, iu 1914, has been started here\nby Alfred Cypreansen of Eau Claire.\nHe was selected by the executive\ncommittee that met here several\nweeks ago to undertake the work. Mr.\nCypreansen is attempting to secure\nSIOO pledges from fifty citizens of the\nstate. He will visit Stoughton and Ed\ngerton and will then go to Milwaukeo\nand Racine to continue the work.\nNovember Fires Cause $316,043 Loss\nNovember fires were more num\nerous and total losses larger than in\nthe same month last year, judging\nfrom State Fire Marshal Clem P.\nHost's monthly report. Fires number\n222, as against 187 in November, 1912.\nand losses $316,043, compared with\n$258,330. Total insurance on damaged\nproperties is $508,075. as against sl,-\n610,325 for the same month last year\nExcept for fires from unknown\ncauses (34) matches proved the most\nprolific source of fires reported. Care\nlessness with children and mice with\nmatches resulted in 26 fires and dam-\nage of $20,087. Chimneys and sparks\ncaused 25 fires and losses of $22,355.\nIncendiary and suspicious numbered\n17 with damage of $34,410. Gasoline\nfires of various nature were 11 in\nnumber and damage of $34,365 result\ned. Seventeen lightning fires were re\nported. against which losses of $24,610\nensued.\nLabor Market Conditions.\nThe depression in the labor market\nnoted in the reports of the state free\nemplovment offices in October became\nmarked in November. For every 100\njobs there were 145 applicants for em\nployment during this month. In Octo\nber there were only 107 and in Novem\nber of last year there were only 101\napplicants for every 100 jobs. The\nwomen\u2019s department of the employ\nment offices for the first time in sev\neral years shows a greater supply of\nlabor than demand. For every 100\nwomen wanted there were 113 appli\ncants for work in November, whereas\na mouth ago the applicants numbered\nI onlv 88 and in November, 191? only\nj s3\nFair Board to Fix Date.\nArguing that the holding of the an\nnual state fair during the last week\nI in August would result in better race\nattractions, larger exhibits and great\ner attendance. Secretary James C. Mc-\nKenzie of the state board of agricul\nture. upon his return from Chicago,\nsaid he favored the earlier date. Mr.\nKenzie at nded the annual meeting\nof the Western Fair and Exposition\nassociatior in that city.\nNew Corporations.\nArticles of incorporation were hied\nin the office of Secretary of State Don\nald as follows\nPort Wing Fruit Growers and farm\ners\u2019 association. Port Wing; capital.\n$1,090; incorporators, Erich Johnson.\nOla? Bodeen. S. A Swanson, Oscar Ol\nson, >l. W. Cochrane.\nThe Sturgeon Bay Land and Devel\nopment company, a Minnesota corpora\nDon. with $25,000 capital, all iu Wis\nconsin. filed a statement to do business\nin the state. j\nMADISON OFFICER\nSLAIN 6V BURGLAR\nWATCHMAN IS SHOT TO DEATH\nWHEN HE DISCOVERS SAFE\nBLOWER AT WORK.\nSI,OOO REWARD FOR ARREST\nAmer Tobacco Company, Whose\nWarehouse Was Being Robbed,\nPosts Offer for Capture\u2014Shot\nGun Is Weapon Used.\nMadison\u2014John Longfield, watchman\nt tiie American Tobacco company\nwarehouse, was shot and killed by a\nburglar whom he found trying to open\nthe safe. The body was found the\nnext morning. A shotgun was used.\nLongfield, who leaves a family, has\nbeen employed as janitor of several\nbusiness blocks.\nGov. McGovern received a telegram\nfrom T. J. Maloney, president of the\nAmerican Tobacco company, offering\nSI,OOO reward for the capture of the\nburglars who shot and killed Long\nfield. It reads:\n\u201cGov. McGovern, Madison, Wis.: We\nauthorize you on behalf of the P. L.\nLorillard company, to offer a reward\nof SI,OOO for the capture and convic\ntion of the burglars who killed our\nnight watchman, John Longfield, while\nin the faithful performance of his\nduty.\u201d\nINDIANS DIVE Tor bodies\nHalfbreed Experts Recover Body of\nOne of Three Girts Drowned in\nLake Geneva Last Summer.\nDelavan.\u2014Two halfblood Indians,\nJohn Jeremy and son of Stillwater,\nMinn., were successful after eight\ndays\u2019 work in finding the body of one\nof the three girls from Pella, la., who\nwere drowned in Lake Geneva last\nsummer.\nThese men came here fresh from\ntheir success in finding the bodies of\na father and son in Lake Mendota at\nMadison, Wis., after all others had\ngiven up the task. Should tiie experts\nbe successful in finding the other two\nbodies of thfe dead girls they will re\nceive a reward of SI,OOO.\nFew bodies of those drowned in\nLake Geneva are ever recovered, es\npecially if it occurs in deep water. In\nsome places the lake is more than\n300 feet deep and being fed almost\nwholly by spring w-ater it is ice cold,\nthus preventing decomposition. The\nnames of the sisters drowned were\nDeguiese and the name of the other\nGezell. Many relatives of the two\ngirls from Pella, la., have been at\nWilliams Bay, Wis., watching the\nwork.\nYOUTH BEST CORN GROWER\nHonor Awarded by University Ex\nperts for Yield of 133 Bushels,\n39 Pounds Per Acre.\nFond du Lac. \u2014Paul Kosclinick, aged\n20, son of Mr. and Mrs. Charles Kos\nchnick, town of Eden, is champion\ncorn grower of Wisconsin, having\nsmashed all records with the yield\nof 133 bushels and thirty-nine pounds\nper acre. The former state record\nwas 133 bushels. The honor was\nawarded by Prof. C. P. Norgord and\nA. If Stone of the state university at\nthe Fond du Lac County Corn and\nGrain show. Koschnick\u2019s record was\ncertified by a committee which super\nvised the whole harvest.\nPHYSICIANS MAKE A KICK\nClaim Eugenic Examination Fee o)\n$3,00, Provided by Law, Is\nFar Too Low.\nRacine.\u2014Racine city and county\nphysicians will refuse to act under the\nnew state eugenic marriage law, which\nprovides that all males must be ex\namined before marriage. The local\nphysicians at a meeting of tiie County\nMedical society declared against ac\ncepting any appointments because the\nfee of $3 provided by law is too low.\nThey claim tiie bare expense of the\ntest totals more than $5. Dr. John M.\nBeffel. Milwaukee, said no self-respect\ning physician will act under the eu\ngenic law for tiie present fee.\nState Laws Protect Freshmen.\nMadison. \u2014Atty. Gen. Owen declared\nthat if any upper classman at the uni\nversity. forcibly ejected a freshman\nfrom a saioor. he would be guilty of\nassault and battery. \u201cTraditions\namount to nothing when it comes to\nenforcing them in the same sense as\nthe laws of tiie state.\" he said.\nWant New Government.\nWhitewater. \u2014A petition is being cir\nculated asking for a vote on the com\nmission form of government.\nGrowers Hold Back Potatoes.\nFond du Lac.\u2014Four hundred and\nfifty empty potato cars were counted\non railroad track* here in one day.\nThe condition resulted from a deter-\nmination of Wisconsin growers not to\nship until prices advance.\nGreen Bay Man a Suicide.\nGreen Bay.\u2014Giving a child 5 cent*\nto break the news to his wife and\nchildren. Adolph Frederick, aged 60 j\nyears, committed suicide by drinking\nacid at his flour milt\nSEEN AND HEARD\nIN WISCONSIN\nAshland.\u2014Poval Jasurda, a farmer,\nfell from a train while boarding it and\nwas fatally injured.\nLa Crosse\u2014Peter Hellem was found\ndead in his bed by his wife on the\nmorning of the fiftieth anniversary of\nbis birth\nWest Salem \u2014Mr. and Mrs Martin\nB. Ladd, residents of this village since\n186S. have just celebrated the sixty\nthird anniversary of their wedding.\nOshkosh \u2014John Howard Kitz, an in\nsurance solicitor, died after being\nstruck by a train while riding on his\nbicycle.\nGrand Rapids\u2014The breaking of a\nhigh tension transmission line carrying\n4,000 volts caused the instant death of\nSamuel Zdnok.\nBaraboo \u2014John Kramer of Green\nfield sold a 720 pound hog for $50.40.\nTwenty-five years ago a hog of this\nweight would have sold for $20.80.\nLa Crosse \u2014Peter Helm was found\ndead in bed. His wife and friends had\nplanned to celebrate his fiftieth birth\nday anniversary.\nI-a Crosse.\u2014Rev. John Andrew Pad\ndock has been installed as the new pas\ntor of the Presbyterian church at Ban\ngor, Rev. Finch A. Clark of this city\nofficiating.\nGreen Bay.\u2014-Over 100 priests of\nGreen Bay diocese assembled here in\nannual eucharistic conference at St.\nJoseph\u2019s orphanage. Bishop Fox pre\nsided.\nFond du Lac. Robert Rioedel.\ndeputy warden at the state prison\nat Waupun, sent his resignation to the\nstate board of control. He said he\nwould issue a statement later.\nManitowoc\u2014Mrs. Anna Hartman,\nwife of a prominent farmer of the\ntown of Schleswig, committed suicide\nby drinking paris green In a quantity\nof coffee. No cause is given for the\nact.\nMadison.\u2014Rev. A. V Mueller of\nRandom Lake has been appo'nted\npastor of Holy Redeemer Catholic\nchurch of this city to succeed the late\nRev. H. J. Dreis, and will arrive be\nfore Christmas.\nGreen Day\u2014The Chicago and North-\nWestern railroad company now has a\ncrew of men at work at this point in\nstalling its interlocking and signal\nservice. The system will run from\nDuck Creek to Fond du Lac\nMadison.\u2014Architects of Wisconsin\nare invited to enter a competi\ntion for plans for the Wisconsin\nstate building at the San Francisco\nexposition. Plans must be submitted\nby December 23.\nAshland.-\u2014Bayfield county is mak\ning splendid progress in making\nthe head of the bay road to Ashland a\npermanent structure. By next spring\nit will have put over SIO,OOO on this\npiece of road.\nColumbus.\u2014Rev. Vernon Emery,\npastor of the Congregational church\nhere for the last three years,\nlias accepted a call to become the\npastor of the Congregational church\nat Wellington. O.\nKenosha.\u2014Archie C. Wright, former\nly of this city, was killed at Detroit,\nMich. He was twenty-six years of age\nand an elect rician. His father and\nmother left only a short time ago for\nScotland.\nLa Crosse\u2014Gustave A. Strahlke, a\nfireman in Heilman's brewery, is lying\nat the point of death as the result of\nthe explosion of a lump of pitch w hich\nhe had put into the firebox. He was\nburned by the stream of flying pitch\nand red hot coals.\nAshland\u2014Relatives of Joe Denomie,\nan Indian, who was shot and killed\nten years ago. have started a suit to\nbreak his will by which his attorney\nwas to receive one-fourth of the es\ntate\u2014s2o,ooo. The attorney\u2019s widow\nis trying to collect the money.\nM automa. \u2014Theodore, eight-year-old\nfcon of Mr. and Mrs. T. Songe.\nwest of this village, drowned while\nskating on a small pond on his fath\ner's farm. There were several other\nsmall children on the ice at the time\nand when young Songe broke through\nthey became frightened and ran.\nAshland.\u2014Poval Jasurda, a twen\nty-one-year-old farmer living near\nPhillips, went to the village and\nboarded a logging train, intending to\ntry to get a job in a iumber camp. He\nfell from a car and was fatally injured,\ndying before he could reach an Ash\nland hospital.\nAppleton. The funeral of the\nlate mayor, Dr. James V Cana\nan, was held from St. Mary\u2019s church.\nFather Fitzmaurice officiating Tiie\nKnights of Columbus. Catholic\nKnights, Foresters, the Outagamie\nCounty Medical society and city offi\ncials attended in a body. Detail* from\nthe fire and police departments acted\nas escorts. There are several candi\ndates mentioned for the vacancy The\ncouncil will probably designate a day\nfor the primary. It is thought the elec\ntion will be held in January Under\nthe new law the mayor will receive\nonly $3,000 instead of $3,500, the sal\nary which Doctor Canavan received,\nthere having beeu a cut in cities Of\nthis size under the commission form.\nJanesville\u2014Representative of a\nwealthy and influential family, Peret\nMerrell. arrested and bid under\nSI,OOO ball for alleged firing of\na freight car in rear of factory,\nwas recently released from the state\nasylum w here he was committed after\nconfessing to burning property valued\nat $50,000.\nWhitewater.\u2014 William VcLace. aged\nthirty-six, clerk for five years,\ncommitted suicide by hanging him\nself on his fa r m. He bad been in\npoor health for i number of years.\nWhen found he was still alive, but\ndied soon after removal to the house.","height":"21540","width":"15222"}}
